\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Results of the rising bubble at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1000\ \text{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Solid lines are the multi-fluid, single column solutions of the rising
 bubble.
 Dashed lines are the single fluid, resolved solutions.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If there is no drag between fluids, no transfers, no diffusion and the pressures
 of both fluids are assumed equal then the multi-fluid equations are unstable
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "TEB19"

\end_inset

.
 The simulation with (
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

) in the top row of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn-bad"

\end_inset

 actually has small transfers to prevent either 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 from becoming negative.
 This is sufficient to stabilise the solution but does not prevent oscillations
 from developing in all fields.
 The buoyant fluid has risen very little from the initial conditions.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 oscillates between zero and one meaning that only one fluid is present
 at some locations so there is no possibility for the fluids to move past
 each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Including entrainment and detrainment as 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}=-\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 stabilises the solution and enable the fluids to move past each other even
 without pressure differences between the fluids (second row of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn-bad"

\end_inset

).
 However too much is detrained from fluid 1, fluid 1 looses too much buoyancy
 and a discontinuity arises at the bubble leading edge; the buoyancy force
 is producing vertical motion but there is no pressure to make it smooth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using entrainment and detrainment set by divergence (
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}=-\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

) and pressure difference between the fluids controlled by divergence (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}=P-\gamma\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

) simulations are more realistic (bottom three rows of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn-bad"

\end_inset

).
 Three values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 are tested.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is set from equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gammaDimAnal"

\end_inset

) using a length scale equal to the bubble radius and a buoyancy scale equal
 to the initial maximum buoyancy to give 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=2.3\times10^{4}\text{m}^{2}\text{s}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 (third row of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn-bad"

\end_inset

) makes the velocity profile too smooth and the updraught too weak so the
 bubble does not rise enough.
 It is reasonable to consider smaller values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 because the buoyancy does not retain its initial maximum for very long.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=10^{4}\text{m}^{2}\text{s}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 gives more accurate solutions whereas using 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=4\times10^{3}\text{m}^{2}\text{s}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 leads to the leading edge of the bubble rising too quickly.
 Smaller values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 leave a discontinuity in the updraught velocity at the leading edge of
 the bubble and larger values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 reduce the velocity further, meaning that the bubble does not rise enough
 (not shown).
 None of the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 reproduce the peak updraught velocities but 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=10^{4}\text{m}^{2}\text{s}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 comes closest, meaning that the bubble rise and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

 are approximately correct and pressure increases above the centre of the
 bubble are realisitic.
 The large low pressure at the bottom of the bubble is not reproduced.
 This is located at the lobes of the highest buoyancy in the resolved simulation
 (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bubble"

\end_inset

).
 It would be tempting to model this by assuming hydrostatic pressure or
 the Bernouilli equation, but these are both forms of the momentum equation
 which is used to calculate the velocity and so cannot also be used to model
 the pressure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results in the top row of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn"

\end_inset

 use 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=-10^{4}\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}=-\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 but this time with drag set by 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{D}/r_{c}=1/2000\text{m}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 The drag slows the updraughts without increasing the mixing between the
 fluids which makes the solutions less like the resolved simulations.
 Although drag is known to be an important term in the momentum equations
 for buoyant thermals and plumes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "eg"
key "RC15"

\end_inset

, the drag is related to mixing with downdraught air which is accounted
 for in the entrainment term of the momentum equation.
 So adding a separate term from drag risks double counting and slows the
 plume too much.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we include pressure difference between fluids with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=10^{4}\text{m}^{2}\text{s}^{-1}$
\end_inset

but omit entrainment (
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

) (second row of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn"

\end_inset

) the fluids move past each other but there is an unrealistic discontinuity
 with no fluid 1 below the buoyant fluid and very little falling air at
 the lowest height of the rising fluid.
 With a single column and two fluids, all air must rise in one fluid and
 sink in the other.
 Continuity does not allow for any other solution.
 Pressure gradients can accelerate or decelerate this flow but as the model
 is set up, with no transfers between fluids, no fluid can change direction.
 It is therefore essential to have transfers between fluids.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other entrainment option is the commonly used fractional entrainment
 rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=0.2/r_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 This is used combined with pressure differences between fluids in the bottom
 row of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn-bad"

\end_inset

.
 This combination produces smooth solutions but the updraught is too weak
 and too much is entrained into fluid 1.
 Using this entrainment, the updraught will entrain more and more air until
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}=-\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 model gives much more accurate entrainment and detrainment for this test
 case using conditional averaging based on 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two alternative models for estimating the buoyancy of the fluid transferred
 between updraught and downdraught have been tested.
 The results in the fourth row if figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn"

\end_inset

 assume that the fluid transferred has zero buoyancy in order to keep the
 positively buoyant air in fluid one and the negatively buoyant air in fluid
 0.
 Thus when zero buoyancy air leaves fluid one (the updraught), the mean
 buoyancy of fluid one increases.
 This leads to very high buoyancy in fluid one which is not present in the
 resolved simulation.
 The results in the bottom row of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn"

\end_inset

 use 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{ij}^{T}=\frac{1}{2}\left(b_{0}+b_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TEB19"

\end_inset

 so that the fluid transferred is influenced by the fluid it is moving towards
 as well as where it has come from.
 This again leads to very large buoyancy in fluid one and also negative
 buoyancy in fluid zero which should not occur for this test case.
 These simple models reinforce the idea that the buoyancy of the fluid transferr
ed should depend on knowledge of sub-grid-scale variability of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 within each fluid – these simple assumptions can lead to unrealistic behaviour.
 The best model tested is 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{ij}^{T}=b_{i}$
\end_inset

 which assumes that the fluid transferred takes the mean properties with
 it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section has demonstrated the value of using a single column, multi-fluid
 model to simulate a buoyant rising bubble with a single updraught fluid
 and a single downdraught fluid.
 Transfers between the fluids have been successfully modelled using entrainment
 set by divergence and the pressure difference between the fluids has also
 been represented by divergence.
 There are clearly discrepancies between the single fluid resolved rising
 bubble and the two fluid single column rising bubble but we do not want
 to over fit the multi-fluid model to one, dry, two dimensional test case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Radiative-Convective Equilibrium (RCE)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A two-dimensional, dry radiative convective equilibrium test case is devised
 to mimic some properties of atmospheric convection, in particular the difficult
y resolving the flow at coarse resolution.
 The domain is 160km wide, 10km tall and is resolved by 640 cells in the
 horizontal and 40 in the vertical (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x=\Delta z=250$
\end_inset

m).
 The top and bottom boundaries are zero velocity and the lateral boundaries
 are periodic.
 A heat flux of 
\begin_inset Formula $h=10^{-3}\text{m}^{2}\text{s}^{-3}$
\end_inset

 is imposed at the bottom boundary leading to a boundary condition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial b/\partial z=-h/\alpha\text{s}^{-2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=100\ \text{m}^{2}\text{s}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the buoyancy diffusivity.
 The top boundary has 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial b/\partial z=0$
\end_inset

.
 Diffusion is applied to the momentum equation with a coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=70.7\ \text{m}^{2}\text{s}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 so as to give a Plank constant of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.707$
\end_inset

.
 Uniform cooling of 
\begin_inset Formula $-1\times10^{-7}\text{m}\text{s}^{-3}$
\end_inset

 is applied to the domain to maintain equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fluid is initially stationary with 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

.
 In order to quickly and reproducibly initialise instability, 
